div.p: A Diſtinct and Faithful ACCOMPT OF ALL THE RECEIPTS, Disburſments, and Remainder OF THE MONEYS COLLECTED IN ENGLAND, VVALES & IRELAND, For the Relief of the poor diſtreſſed PROTESTANTS IN THE Valleys of Piemont, Together with a Brief Accompt of the preſent State of Affairs in thoſe Parts; As well for the better Satisfaction of all thoſe who have already contributed, as for the Encouragement of thoſe who have as yet been wanting toward ſo good and charitable a Work.

p.hi: Printed and Publiſhed by ſpecial Order of His Highneſs and the Council.

div.p: LONDON: Printed by HEN. HILLS and JOHN FIELD, Printers to His Highneſs. Anno Dom. 1658.

div.head: A NARRATIVE Publiſhed by the ſpecial Order of His Highneſs The Lord Protector, AND HIS COUNCIL; For the better Satisfaction of all thoſe who have already contributed towards the Relief of the Poor Proteſtants of the Valleys of Piemont, and for the Encouragement of thoſe who are yet behinde to the performance of ſo good and charitable a Work.
div.p: HIs Highneſs the Lord Protector having received intelligence about the month of May, in the year of our Lord 1655. that many hundreds of the Poor Proteſtants in the Valleys of Piemont (otherwiſe known by the name of Waldenſes) within the Territories of the Duke of Savoy, were moſt cruelly maſſacred by a Popiſh party; and having upon his ſpirit a deep ſenſe of their Calamities, which were occaſioned by their faithful Adherence to the profeſſion of the Reformed Religion, was pleaſed, not onely to mediate by moſt pathetick Letters in their behalf, to the King of France, and Duke of Savoy, but did alſo ſeriouſly invite the People of this Nation to ſeek the Lord by Prayer and Humiliation in reference to their then ſad condition, and future relief: And from a confidence that the good People of this Nation would be ſenſibly touched with the afflictions of Joſeph, and in that day of their Brethrens trouble, manifeſt a ſutable reſentment of, and ſympathizing with the Sufferings of their fellow members, profeſsing the ſame Faith and Religion with themſelves, did forthwith publiſh a Declaration, expreſsing his earneſt deſire that the People might be ſtirred up to a free and liberal Contribution towards their Succor and Support: For the Management of which Collection, certain Inſtructions were alſo agreed upon, and annexed to the ſaid Declaration: And for the more effectual promoting of the Work, His Highneſs appointed a Committee, conſiſting of perſons of known Honor, Fidelity and Integrity, to conſider and adviſe from time to time how the Moneys that ſhould be thereupon raiſed, might be imployed with moſt advantage and certainty for the Supply of thoſe poor diſtreſſed Members of Chriſt, according to the true intention of the Givers; amongſt whom likewiſe there were two ſelect Perſons of very conſiderable Eſtate and Reputation, appointed to be Treaſurers for the receiving in the ſaid Moneys, whoſe names, together with the number and names of the Committee aboveſaid, for the better ſatisfaction of the Reader are here inſerted, viz.

Other Lords and Gentlemen.

div.p: Neither was this His Highneſs Chriſtian care and tenderneſs left unanſwered by the open hearts and hands of many charitable and compaſsionate ſouls, both of this Nation and Ireland, who upon the publiſhing of the aboveſaid Declaration and Inſtructions, did moſt freely and chearfully Contribute towards the ſeaſonable Refreſhing the Bowels of their poor afflicted Brethren.

True it is, ſome Pariſhes and particular Perſons of note there were, amongſt whom there was at that time obſerved ſome kinde of backwardneſs to this good Work; (yea many there are to this very day, who do not appear within the Returns to have contributed any thing towards it) however means were alſo uſed for ſupplying that defect, and that by a ſubſequent Proclamation, which was afterwards reinforced by His Highneſs punctual Orders to the Juſtices of Peace in the ſeveral Counties, to examine in their reſpective Diviſions at what places no Collections had been made; and in caſe of Collections made, where the Money had not been ſent up, and to cauſe a ſpeedy return to be made thereof; By which means, through the great goodneſs of God, and bleſsing upon His Highneſs endeavors (though it may be juſtly feared that there were defaults in ſome places, and the money not to this day delivered in to the Treaſurers) there were conſiderable Sums in a ſhort ſpace of time brought in, and carefully lodged in the Treaſury, ready to be iſſued out and diſtributed, as there ſhould be ways and means found for the ſafe conveyance thereof into the reſpective places, where thoſe poor wretches
had then their abode, which was in the Clefts of ragged Rocks, and in the Caves of ſnowy Mountains.

For this very end and purpoſe His Highneſs (continuing His care for carrying on this Work) did at the ſame time conſtitute and appoint Mr. Pell (His Reſident with the Proteſtant Cantons of Switzerland) and Mr. Morland (whom he had not long before ſent as His Envoy to the King of France and Duke of Savoy, in their behalf) as His Joynt-Commiſsioners Extraordinary for the management of this Affair beyond Sea, who were likewiſe furniſhed with ſutable Inſtructions and Commands, to the end that by their ſpecial inſpection and care, the collected Moneys might not onely be remitted from England into the Valleys, with expedition, ſecurity, and at the eaſieſt rates; but likewiſe, that being thus conveyed, they might be actually diſtributed and laid out for the clothing of the Naked, the feeding of the Hungry, and relieving the Sick, and that with all poſsible equity and juſt proportion, having a due reſpect to the greateſt Sufferers, and moſt neceſsitous amongſt them; the which was accordingly performed by the aboveſaid Mr. Pell and Mr. Morland; and the way and method which they then propounded to His Highneſs and the Council, being approved, things were immediately put in execution; and His Highneſs, upon advice from time to time with the ſaid Committee, did Order the remitting of ſeveral ſums of Money into the Valleys, through the hands firſt of Mr. Pell and Mr. Morland joyntly, and afterwards through the hands of Mr. Morland ſingly (who by His Highneſs Order reſided at Geneva for the ſpace of a whole year, commencing fro • the twentieth of November 1655. for that very end) according to the ſeveral Conjunctures, and preſsing Seaſons of the poor peoples Neceſsities, as they were by him from time to time repreſented to His Highneſs and the Council.

Upon Mr. Morlands Return into England, an Accompt was by him tendred to the ſaid Committee in Ianuary laſt, for the Moneys ſo remitted beyond Sea, and then a Sub-Committee was appointed to receive and examine the ſame (viz. Sir Thomas Vyner, Sir Chriſtopher Pack, and Mr. Creſſet) who had alſo power to call to their aſsiſtance any ſuch perſon as they ſhould think fit as an Auditor, for the punctual Examination and Adjuſting of the ſaid Accompt; which Sub-Committee did on the 21 of Ianuary laſt paſt, make Report to the ſaid Committee, That they had peruſed and examined the Accompt, both as to the Moneys ſent from hence, and that whi • h was by him taken up there, and that upon the whole, they found it to be juſtly ſtated in the Book delivered by Mr. Morland.

Now to the end that publique notice may be given what Moneys have been received upon the ſaid Collections, and from what particular perſons, pariſhes or places within this Nation and Ireland, what Sums have been iſſued out and tranſmitted beyond Sea, and at what rates; what method hath been from time to time obſerved in the management of this Affair, and the reaſon why the ſame hath been ſo diſtributed amongſt the poor people by parts, •• ther then the whole Sums together; and laſtly what yet remains in ſtock, with the method in general which His Highneſs hath propoſed for the imployment thereof for the beſt advantage of thoſe diſtreſſed Proteſtants: And to the end that all the good People of this Commonwealth may receive full ſatisfaction, and be well aſſured that no part of the ſaid collected moneys either hath been, or ſhall hereafter be diverted from the charitable intention of the Donors, but ſolely imployed and diſpoſed to thoſe very Uſes to which they were originally deſigned, His Highneſs hath thought fit to appoint the publiſhing of the following Accompt.

div.head: A Diſtinct, Clear and Exact ACCOMPT As well of what was given by His HIGHNESS in particular, upon the firſt News of their Troubles, as of all other Moneys brought in and received for the Relief of the poor Proteſtants in the Valleys of Piemont, Together with the Names of all, as well Pariſhes and Chappels, as other Places and Congregations in the ſeveral Counties of England, Wales and Ireland, from whence there were any Returns made (excepting onely ſome few Pariſhes and Places in ſeveral Counties, whoſe Moneys were returned without making any ſpecification of their reſpective Names.)
To which is added a Catalogue of the Names of ſeveral particular perſons who then contributed more largely upon that occaſion, with the reſpective Sums by each of them ſo given.

Delivered in to the Right Honorable Commiſſioners appointed by His Highneſs and the Council, for the Management of that Affair, in the Moneth of November 1657. by Sir Thomas Vyner and Sir Chriſtopher Pack, Knights; Treaſurers for the receiving and iſſuing forth the ſaid collected Moneys.

div.head: AN EXTRACT, OR, Abbreviate of the Accompt

Delivered in to the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners for the Valleys of Piemont, by Samuel Morland Eſq as well of the Moneys that were remitted from England, to the poor Proteſtants of the ſaid Valleys, before, and during the time of his reſiding in Geneva, in Quality of His Highneſs Commiſſioner Extraordinary, for the management of thoſe Affairs, as of the Moneys which he remitted ſince his Return, by the Order of His Highneſs, and the Council.
To which is added a Particular of all other Receipts and Disburſements, of, or upon thoſe Moneys, to balance the whole Accompt.
Drawn up by the ſaid Mr Morland, and publiſhed by the Special Order of His Highneſs and the Council.

div.p: UPon the 20/30th of Nov. 1655. Maſter Pell and Maſter Morland His Highneſs Commiſſioners Extraordinary for the Management of the Affairs of the poor Proteſtants of the Valleys beyond-ſea, (and eſpecially of the collected Moneys) then reſiding at Geneva, by His Highneſs Orders, for that very end and purpoſe, received a Letter written to them joyntly, by the Right Honorable M. Secretary Thurloe, bearing date the 08/18 Nov. 1655, wherein they were ordered to diſtribute forthwith that part of the collected Moneys that had been remitted into the hands of M. Lodwick Calandrine, Merchant of Geneva, an Extract of which Letter is here inſerted as follows:

body.head: Copie of Maſter Secr. Thurloes Letter to M. Pell, and M. Morland, bearing date the 08/18 Novemb. 1655.
body.p:
HIs Highneſs and the Council, having taken into conſideration what you have repreſented concerning the condition of the poor perſecuted Waldenſes, inhabiting the Valleys of Piemont, have reſolved, that ſeven thouſand five hundred pounds ſterling ſhall be diſtributed amongst them, for their preſent relief; And there being five thouſand pounds
already in the hands of Master Lodwick Calandrine, Merchant of Geneva, and two thouſand five hundred pounds more charged by Bill of Exchange a Moneth ſince, to be paid unto him; I have writ unto him, to pay, as well the 5000 l. as the 2500 l. as you two ſhall appoint: And His Highneſs pleaſure is, That you cauſe a Distribution of the ſaid Money to be made amongst the poor Proteſtants, having reſpect therein, 〈◊〉 thoſe of them, who are most neceſſitous, and have received the greatest prejudice by the late Maſſacre and Perſecution; wherein it is not poſſible for Ʋs here to give you particular Rules, but the doing thereof must be left to your prudent Management: And for the reſidue of the Money collected upon this occaſion, further conſideration will be had, to the end that it may be employed for the most advantage; And you are to take ſuch courſe in the Diſtribution of the Money, That an Exact Accompt may be given, how it hath been diſpoſed of. I rest

div.p: Upon the receipt of this Letter M. Pell and M. Morland immediately conſulted how they might in the beſt Manner execute theſe their Orders; And after they had ſeriouſly conſidered thereof, they reſolved (as they thought themſelves in duty obliged) to make a narrow ſearch into the Way and Method how the former ſumme of 2000 l. ſterl, (which His Highneſs ſent thoſe poor people upon the firſt news of their troubles) had been conveighed from Geneva into the Valleys; That ſo, if they found that Method the moſt advantageous, they might follow the ſame; but if not, That they might endeavour to finde out a better.

Now upon a full enquiry, and after ſeveral diſcourſes had with ſome, and Informations from others, whom they judged the moſt fit to adviſe with in this Affair, They thought it moſt expedient in that Conjuncture of time (for ſeveral reaſons which can not here conveniently be ſpecified) to receive the ſaid 7500 l. ſterl. of M. Lodwick Calandrine, and compound with another (who alſo muſt be nameleſs) for the ſpeedy conveighance thereof into the Valleys, at his own peril, (which neither M. Calandrine or any other would undertake at any rates) for 926 French Livers.

table.head: Moneys received of Mr Calandrine by Mr Pell and Mr Morland.

row.cell: Item, Mr L. Cal. chargeth for changing and conveighing one part of the ſaid 95590 Fr. Liv. viz. 31670. Fr. Liv. from Lyons to Geneva
Item, For his Proviſion and Charges for the firſt ſumme of 63648 Liv.
Item, For his Proviſion and Charges for the laſt Summe of 31950 Fr. Liv.

div.p: Which Summe of 96428 Fr. Liv. 11 Sols is the very ſumme which the Right Honorable Commiſſioners in England agreed for with Major Chamberlain, to be paid at Lyons, as aboveſaid.

Now Mr Pell and Mr Morland having received the aboveſaid ſumme of 96428 Liv. 11 Sols into their own hands, did immediately remit the ſame into the Valleys for 926 Fr. Liv. as aboveſaid (as will appear in the ſequel of this Chapt. by the Original Acquittance of the poor people themſelves.) But withal taking into their ſerious conſiderations the urgent neceſſities of the poor people at that time, having neither bread to eat, nor clothes to cover their nakedneſs, nor indeed the leaſt accommodation
for a great multitude of ſick, weak and aged perſons among them, did forthwith imploy certain perſons of known fidelity, and who bore a real and undoubted affection towards the poor people and their Cauſe, forthwith to lay out ſuch a proportion of the 95598 Liv. aboveſaid, in the buying of ſuch quantities of Corn, Cloth, Bedding, Shoes, Linen and Medicaments, as their neceſsities did then call for, and to diſtribute the ſame to every family diſtinctly, according to the number of perſons therein contained.

Here (by the way) it will not be amiſs to inform the Reader, that before this 7500 l. or any part thereof, was remitted into the hands of Mr. Pell and Mr. Morland; That is to ſay, upon the firſt News of the Maſſacre, His Highneſs ſent the poor people upon his own private accompt, the ſum of 2000 l. Sterling, which was remitted by the Correſpondents of Mr. Luke Lucy, at the rate of 56½ Engliſh pence for a French Crown of 3 Livers; which 2000 l. Sterling after the ſaid rate, amount to the ſum of 25486 Fr. Liv. 12 Sols, and 6 Deniers, and was moreover in the conveighance, by the advantage of the Species, augmented and made 25510 Livers. Now foraſmuch as this Sum was actually received by the poor people, and laid out for their Supplies in the time of their extream Neceſſities, (as will appear by their own Acquittance, the Original whereof was delivered up by Mr. Morland to the Right Honorable Commiſſioners) it will be moſt convenient to prefix the ſame to the following Accompt, which will then conſiſt of 9500 l. Sterling.

It now remains onely, that the Original and Authentique Acquittances of the poor people themſelves, be produced for the above-ſpecified ſum of 120182 Fr. Liv. for the
value of 9500 l. Sterling; That is to ſay, the Remainder of 121938 Fr. Liv. 11 Sols, after the aboveſaid Deduction, firſt by M. Calandrine 830 F. Liv. 11 Sols, and afterwards by M. Pell and M. Morland 926 F. Liv. A true Tranſlat of which Acquittance is here inſerted, the Original whereof was delivered to the Right Honorable Commiſsioners by M. Morland, at his return from Geneva into England.

body.head: Tranſlat of the Original Acquittances of the Poor Proteſtants of the Valleys of Piemont, made at S. Giovanni in the Valleys of Lucerna 14/24 Auguſt 1656.
body.p: WE the Deputies of the Reformed Churches of the Valleys of Piemont, do confeſs to have received of the Moneys collected in England, for our relief, as follows:

Firſt of all, We confeſs to have received through the hands of M. Calandrine and other Merchants of Geneva, the ſum of Twenty five thouſand five hundred and ten Fr. Livers, in the Moneth of July 1655. which came very ſeaſonably for the ſupplying our extream neceſsities.

Item, We confeſs to have received of M. Pell and M. Morland, His Highneſs Commiſsioners Extraordinary, in the Moneths of January and February 1656. the ſum of Ninety four thouſand ſix hundred ſeventy two French Livers; the which ſum was imployed and laid out in Coverings for Beds, Linen for Shifts, and other Neceſſaries, in Corn for Seed, and preſent ſpending, in Medicaments, and other Neceſſaries for ſick people; and laſtly for ſupplying the more urgent neceſsities of ſeveral particular perſons.

Both which ſums aboveſaid, have been remitted to us by the Order of His Highneſs the Lord Protector, whoſe ſingular Zeal and Charity for the poor diſtreſſed Members of Chriſt, which ſuffer for the Truth, we cannot ſufficiently admire; And as the Lord hath raiſed Him as a moſt Illuſtrious Example of Chriſtian and Heroique Vertues, we beſeech him from the very bottom of our hearts, that he will be pleaſed likewiſe to make him an Example of his extraordinary Bleſsing; And that he will alſo be pleaſed out of the abundant Riches both of his ſpiritual and temporal Graces, reward the Churches of Great Britain, who have been ſo touched with our Miſeries, and with ſo much pity and compaſſion refreſhed our Bowels, that ſo we may have always matter of rejoycing and bleſsing his holy Name for the welfare and prosperity of that Commonwealth. Even ſo Amen.
In teſtimony whereof we have ſubſcribed the 14 Auguſt 1656.

div.p: The true Original of this Acquittance (being ſubſcribed by ſeveral perſons, whoſe Names it is thought fit for ſeveral weighty reaſons to conceal) was delivered by M. Morland into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners, appointed by His Highneſs & the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs.

Thus were the Bowels of thoſe poor Creatures exceedingly refreſhed for a ſeaſon. But alas it was not long before they had need of freſh Supplies, for they had neither any certain habitation, nor any opportunity or means to till their Lands, or to traffique for their future ſubſiſtence, being altogether deſtitute of Cattel and all other Materials and Utenſils, inſomuch that whatſoever was diſtributed amongſt them, ſerved but for very little more then from hand to mouth, and to ſupply their preſent neceſsities. The plain truth is, the condition of thoſe poor Creatures was then (and God knows is to this very day) very ſad and lamentable. On the one ſide, what was then given them, did onely ſerve to fortifie Nature to be more ſenſible of Hunger, Cold, and the Miſeries of this Life, and to enable them to cry for more relief; and on the other ſide, to have given them greater Sums at a time, would have moſt certainly expoſed them to the fury of thoſe ravenous evening Wolves, who would much ſooner, and with ſeven-fold more greedineſs have ſet upon, and devoured thoſe poor Lambs, had they had but golden fleeces upon their Backs.

Wherefore it was then Reſolved (as the ſecureſt way) by His Highneſs and the Council, That the poor people might be ſupplyed from time to time, ſo as they might ſubſiſt, until Providence ſhould open a way for the obtaining for them ſome kinde of ſettlement and re-eſtabliſhment.

By this the Reader may eaſily conjecture, how ſoon there was like to be further occaſion of ſolliciting His Highneſs and the Council for new ſupplies, the which Mr Morland accordingly from time to time did, that Affair being now wholly committed to his charge alone; and Mr Pell (according to His Highneſs Orders) being now returned to his former employment of Reſidency at Zurick.

And having an opportunity in the Interval of time, to conſider the inconveniencies of the former Remiſſion of the collected Moneys from England to Geneva, eſpecially as to the dear rates, and alſo the great diſtance of time it had upon the way (which notwithſtanding as Affairs then ſtood, when the ſaid Moneys were remitted, could not eaſily be prevented, though the Right Honorable Committee uſed therein their utmoſt endeavors) whereas the poor people had preſent and urgent occaſion for Moneys; And foraſmuch as it was not at that time altogether improbable that they might have been ſet upon on a ſudden, and ſo have periſhed for want of ſpeedy relief, the ſaid Mr Morland began to inform himſelf, in order to the finding out a more ſpeedy and profitable way for the conveighance of the ſaid Moneys for the future; And at laſt he met with a certain perſon, who made him a Propoſition as follows; Namely,

That for 2 per 100 he would undertake to advance any ſumme or ſummes of Money in any of thoſe parts, in caſe Mr. Morland would aſſure him, that he ſhould be repaid at London; And all this according to the ordinary rate of Exchange of Moneys from Paris to London; And ſo by conſequence any ſumme of Moneys might upon any occaſion be remitted from London to the Valleys in the ſpace of 15 or 16 days, and all for 2 per 100.
This Propoſition Mr Morland communicated into England, and received an Anſwer to it of the 7 Febr. 5/6; an Extract whereof is here inſerted, viz.

body.head: Extract of the R. Honorable Mr Secretary Thurloe's Letter of the 7 Febr. 1655/6;.
body.p: I Have communicated your Expedient for returning Moneys, and I have ſent you the incloſed Papers, which you are to conſider; And if you can contract to take up Moneys ſo as theſe Papers ſtate it, you are to make ſure of 7000 l. ſterl. And you may charge the Bills for it upon Sir Thomas Viner and Sir Chriſtopher Pack, Aldermen of the Citie of London, and they will be duly paid: But be ſure you make your Bargain ſafe and with good advice. And alſo how to diſpoſe of the Money (which must be ready at Geneva) for which you ſhall have Order afterwards.

div.p: Upon the receipt of this, and after a mature conſideration, Mr Morland made an Accord with the perſon aboveſaid in the following terms.

body.head: A Tranſlat of the Accord made between Samuel Morland Eſq His Highneſs Commiſſioner Extraordinary on the one part, and J.N. on the other, for the remitting of 7000 l. from England to Geneva.
body.p:
I Whoſe name is here under-written, out of Conſideration had to the poor people of Piemont, have contracted with Sam. Morland Eſq His Highneſs Commiſſioner Extraordinary for the ſumme of ſeven thouſand pounds ſterling, for the which ſhall be furniſht me Bills of Exchange payable to J. N. and J. S. or according to their Order, at firſt ſight, at the rate of 54 pence and 3 farthings for every crown of 3 Livers Tournois. For the which I hereby promiſe to pay the value to the ſaid Mr. Morland by advance, in Spaniſh Piſtols, or French gold Piſtols at 10 Livers 10 Sols the Piſtol, and French Louis or Crowns, at 3 Livers the Crown; The ſaid Mr. Morland promiſing me on his part, that the ſaid Bils of Exchange which he ſhall deliver me, ſhall be duly paid me; As alſo making good to me two in the hundred, which ſhall be in conſideration both of advancing
the Moneys here, and alſo for the Charges it will occaſion me, and the hazard I run, together with all ſorts of Proviſions.

And beſides this I promiſe, That in caſe the Exchange from Paris to London come to be abated within the ſpace of 15 days lower then the ſaid price of 54 pence per crown, to make the ſame good to Mr. Morland, for the benefit of the poor people: And on the contrary, in caſe it come to be higher, he ſhall make the ſame good to me. Foraſmuch as I pretend nothing more or leſs then the ſaid 2 per 100 for the advance of the Moneys, the proviſion, and the hazard which I run. In witneſs whereof we have ſigned this preſent Accord, in two Copies of the ſame Tenor.

closer.signed: In the preſence of ſeveral perſons whoſe names it's thought fit to conceal, S. Morland. J. N.

div.p: Upon the ſigning of this Accord, there was the value of 7000 l. Sterling as aboveſaid, actually paid M. Morland, and the Bills of Exchange afterwards duly honored by Sir Thomas Vyner and Sir Chriſtopher Pack in London.
The firſt of April M. Morland received a Letter from M. Secretary Thurloe, in anſwer to his of the 26 Feb. and 9 March (wherein he had repreſented the ſad condition of the poor people at that time.)

body.head: Extract of the Right Honorable Mr. Secretary Thurloes Letter to Mr. Morland of the 20 March 1656.
body.p: OF the Seven thouſand pounds Sterling paid unto you, you are forthwith to cauſe Two thouſand pound to be diſtributed amongſt the poor Proteſtants of the Valleys, for the relief of their Neceſsities, taking care that it be done juſtly, and with the beſt advantage for their good, and giving Accompt thereof hither with what ſpeed may be.

div.p: Here it will be neceſſary to advertiſe the Reader, that at that time when Mr. Morland took up the aboveſaid 7000 l. at Geneva, he foreſaw that there was like to be ſome diſtance of time between that of his taking up the Moneys, and the Receipt of his Orders for the Diſtribution thereof, which made him deſirous to improve the ſaid Moneys for the beſt advantage, by putting it out to profit, yet with this caution, That he put it out firſt into ſafe hands: and ſecondly, that he might recall the ſame, if need were, at a days warning, or at two at the moſt; All which he did, and by that means when he received his Orders for the diſtribution of the 2000 l. aboveſaid amongſt the poor people, in ſtead of 2000 l. he ſent 2091 l. 12 s. 6 d. (as will appear by their Original Acquittance) and yet for the 5000 l. remaining, he had left the value of 5010 l. 14 s. 9 d. as will be more clear by the following Accompt.

It will be here likewiſe neceſſary to advertiſe the Reader for his better ſatisfaction, That after Mr. Morland had received his Orders for the Diſtribution of the aboveſaid 2000 l. he was forced by reaſon of the great danger there was of loſs upon the Species in that conjuncture of time, together with the Stratagems of their Adverſaries, who knowing that there was Money coming to them from England and other parts, ſought all means to procure them great loſs upon their Moneys, by obtaining Edicts from the Court of Savoy for that purpoſe; to ſend an Expreſs into the Valleys to inform himſelf punctually what Species would be moſt advantegeous; and ſo there was a Moneths time loſt or more, before he could have the poor peoples Acquittance for the Receipt of the Moneys.

body.head: A Tranſlat of the Original Acquittance of the poor People of the Valleys for 2091 l. 12. s. 6 d. which was delivered into their hands the 29th of May 1656.
body.p: WE the Deputies of the Reformed Churches of the Valleys of Piemont, acknowledge to have received of M. Morland His Highneſs Commiſsioner Extraordinary, the ſum of Twenty ſeven thouſand five hundred and ſix French Livers, and ten Sols, or Two thouſand and ninety one pounds twelve ſhillings ſix pence ſterling, being a part of the Collected Moneys remitted from England, by Order of His Hsghneſs The Lord Protector; The which ſum of Twenty ſeven thouſand five hundred and ſix French Livers, ten Sols, was immediately diſtributed to each particular Church, according to the propoſitioms heretofore eſtabliſhed by Mr. Pell and Mr. Morland, with reſpect had to their Sufferings more or leſs by the late unhappy War and Perſecution raiſed againſt them for the cauſe and ſake of their Religion, in the Year 1655. to the end that every one might receive his juſt portion, and by that means they might in ſome meaſure be relieved according to their preſent neceſsities; for the which we joyn in returning hearty Thanks to the Authors of this charitable Benevolence, beſeeching the Lord to pour down upon them abundantly, as a Reward of their Chriſtian Zeal, both the Bleſsings of this life and that which is to come.

div.p: The true Original of this Acquittance (being ſubſcribed by ſeveral perſons, whoſe Names it is thought fit for ſeveral weighty reaſons to conceal) was delivered by M. Morland into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners, appointed by His Highneſs & the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs.

Mr. Morland after the Diſtribution of the aboveſaid 2091 l. 12 s. 6 d. having a better opportunity and more leiſure to perfect the way and method of the Diſtribution of the Collected Moneys, among the poor Proteſtants, after advice had with thoſe whom he thought moſt fit to counſel him in this matter, at laſt pitcht upon certain Inſtructions, which he cauſed afterwards to be obſerved exactly in the Diſtribution of the remainder of the 7000 l. Sterling, and after that of the laſt 2000 l. Sterling, which he remitted ſince his return. An Extract of which Inſtructions (ſo far as they are fit to be communicated) are here inſerted.

div.head: An Extract of the Inſtructions given by Mr. Morland, to thoſe whom he intruſted for the Diſtribution of the collected Moneys among the poor people of the Valleys of Piemont.
General Articles as touching the Diſtribution.
div.p: I. THoſe who have any Eſtate, be it in moveables or otherwiſe, ought not to expect a Gratuity proportionable to their loſſes; For by this means thoſe who yet remained in ſome tolerable poſture of Subſiſtence after the Invaſion, would devour the whole, or at leaſt the greateſt part of that which ought to relieve thoſe who are in moſt diſtreſs.

II. Thoſe who had almoſt all their Patrimony in Lands, ought to conſider that the exemption from Taxes which was granted them, could do no leſs then eaſe them of a conſiderable part of their loſſes, and they ought by no means now to pretend to the ſame proportion with thoſe who had little or no moveables, and have beſide that been totally ruined.

div.head: The more particular Rules or Articles.
div.p:
1. According to the general Rules aboveſaid, they ſhall proceed more particularly, and diſtinguiſh thoſe who are the moſt neceſsitous at preſent into theſe three following Ranks:
1. Thoſe, who had very little or nothing at all before the Maſſacre.
2. Thoſe, who had enough tolerably to ſubſiſt.
3. Thoſe, who had ſome kinde of abundance.

And thus there ſhall be eſtabliſhed three Claſſes or Orders, namely, a Lower, a Middle, and a Higher, placing the firſt ſort in the loweſt Rank, the ſecond ſort in the middle Rank, and the laſt ſort in the higheſt Rank or Claſsis; provided ſtill that there be no departing from the General Rules above-ſpecified, and that all poſsible equity and due proportion be obſerved amongſt the ſeveral families thus ranged.

div.head: 2. Touching the Ministers.
div.p: The Miniſters ſhall not pretend any thing of Ordinary Salary or Subſiſtence from theſe collected Moneys, becauſe they have been paid otherwiſe by their reſpective Churches, Nevertheleſs they ſhall be compriſed in the Diſtribution for the reparation of loſſes, in the ſame Propoſition with others.

div.head: 3. Thoſe who have been abſent and had their Subſistence in other Countries.
div.p: Thoſe who have been abſent in the time of the Diſtribution, and had their Subſiſtence in other Countries, at the ſame time, ſhall not pretend any thing from the Diſtributions heretofore adminiſtred.

div.head: 4. Thoſe who have been heretofore administred to in the time of their Sickneſs.
div.p: The ſick, who have been heretofore relieved in their ſickneſs with the publique Moneys, ſhall pretend nothing from the former Diſtributions made, foraſmuch as they have already received more then their portion in the time of their neceſſity.

div.head: 5. Thoſe who have been forgotten by neglect.
div.p: Thoſe who have been heretofore forgotten by neglect or otherwiſe in the time of the ſaid Diſtributions, ſhall receive at preſent that which was then their portion: provided that there be no other reaſon of this their not having a divident heretofore, then a bare and ſimple forgetfulneſs and neglect of them.

div.head: 6. The Wounded.
div.p: The wounded perſons ſhall be diſtinguiſhed, into thoſe who have been maimed, and thereby rendred altogether uſeleſs; and thoſe who have in ſome maner recovered the uſe of their Limbs. To the firſt there ſhall be an eſpecial regard had; and the laſt ſhall alſo be ranked in the firſt and beſt Claſſis, provided that there be good Evidence of the damage which they have ſuffered.

div.head: 7. Thoſe who are indebted to the Phyſician in particular.
div.p: Thoſe who owe any thing to the Phyſician in particular, ſhall pay the Phyſician out of their own, becauſe there hath almoſt always been a publique Phyſitian provided; And this would otherwiſe be a door opened to a very great Confuſion.

div.head: 8. Thoſe who have received more then their due in the former Distributions.
div.p: Thoſe who have received more then their due portion in the former Diſtributions, ſhall make reſtitution by a deduction of ſo much of their portion in the preſent Diſtribution.

div.head: 9. Thoſe who have received any thing out of the time of Diſtribution.
div.p: That which hath been formerly given to the poor out of the time of Diſtribution, ſhall not be accounted to them in the preſent Diſtribution; But if there be found any, who had competent Eſtates, who thus received any Moneys, it ſhall be accounted to them. And the Commiſſioners are to take all poſſible care therein, that this Article be obſerved with all equity and uprightneſs.

div.head: 10. The Arrears of the Ministers.
div.p: Thoſe Miniſters, to whom any thing was formerly due before the Maſſacre, ſhall make their addreſs to their ſeveral Churches for payment thereof, and not demand it of the Publique.

div.head: 11. Their Phyſician.
div.p: Their Phyſician ſhall be paid out of the Publique, according to the former agreement made with him. And for the time to come the people of the Valleys ſhall compound with him for a certain ſtipend; provided that he engage to reſide always among them; And for the ſurplus of his maintenance he ſhall be paid for his pains in a moderate way by thoſe particulars who ſhall employ him.

div.head: 12. The Apothecaries and Chirurgions.
div.p: There ſhall be ſtrict Examination had into what the Apothecaries and Chirurgions have provided formerly for thoſe poor people, who are not now able to repay them, and they ſhall be ſatisfied out of the Publique. But as for thoſe who have wherewithal, they ſhall repay the ſaid Apothecaries and Chirurgions out of their own, and not demand it from the Publique.

div.head: 13. Thoſe who have been most active for the Defence of their Countrey.
div.p: Thoſe who pretend Gratifications for their particular Service that they have done for their Countrey, in expoſing their perſons to great dangers, and by enduring Extraordinary hardſhip, ought to content themſelves with this recompence, namely, the good Teſtimony that they have in their own Conſciences to have done worthily, together with the praiſes of all honeſt people, as likewiſe that they have their portion equal with the reſt in the Diſtribution.

div.head: 14. The Loſſes cauſed by the War.
div.p: There ſhall be particular regard had to thoſe loſſes, which have been cauſed by the War, as pillaging, burning, and the like; provided it plainly appear that it hath proceeded from the War, and not from the ſtorms of Thunder, Hail, or other accidents.

div.head: 15. The Alms of Bread, Wine, &c.
div.p: Thoſe who have furniſhed the poor with Bread or Wine in the time of their former deſolations, ſhall not now demand a reward or recompence for the ſame, by reaſon of the great confuſion that would ariſe from thence; As likewiſe it would be a ſhame to bring their charitable actions upon a publique Account.

THere were ſeveral other particulars of conſequence in the ſaid Inſtructions, which (for ſeveral weighty Reaſons) it is thought moſt convenient rather to paſs over, then communicate in a publique way; however theſe may be ſufficient to give the ſober and underſtanding Reader a taſte and reliſh of the whole; and what eare hath been taken in the Management of that Affair. And indeed all that could then be done was but little enough to preſerve thoſe diſtreſſed Creatures from periſhing for want of the neceſſary accommodations of this life.

It was not many Weeks after the Diſtribution of the 2091 l.—12 s.—06 d.—ſterling, before the poor peoples neceſſities began to be renewed. True it is, they did endeavor to the utmoſt to conceal their wants, having ſo lately received an Alms. But however it was in a ſhort ſpace of time too viſible, how • eer divers of them were to being ſtarved to death, or otherwiſe periſhing in a miſerable maner. Whereupon Mr Morland gave ſpeedy notice thereof to His Highneſs and the Council, who immediately
made an Order which he received the 26 of August, in a Letter from Mr Secretary Thurloe to the ſame purpoſe.

body.head: Extract of Mr. Secretary Thurloes Letter of the 14 Aug. 1656.
body.p: YOu will receive herewith the Order of His Highneſs and the Council for diſtributing the 5000 l. amongst the poor Protestants of Piemont, wherein I deſire you as to uſe your wonted care and circumſpection, ſo to diſpatch this with what ſpeed you may; In reſpect I finde a neceſſity for your return as ſoon as you have finiſhed the Diſtribution of this 5000 l.

body.head: A Copy of the Orde of His Highneſs and the Council. Thurſday 14 Aug. 1656. At the Council at Whitehall.
body.p: ORdered by His Highneſs the Lord Protector and the Council, That the 5000 l. of the collected Moneys for the distreſſed Protestants of the Valleys of Piemont, which was formerly returned over into the hands of Mr Morland, and now remaining with him, be distributed among the ſaid Proteſtants by Mr Morland, in the ſame ſort as the former ſummes of Money have been diſtributed amongst them.

closer.signed: Henry Scobell Clerk of the Council.

div.p: Mr Morland having received theſe Orders, forthwith employed his utmoſt endeavors for the ſpeedy Execution of the ſame; But foraſmuch as the ſaid ſumme of 5010 l. 14. s. 9. d. ſterl. or 65894 French Livers 10 Sols, was all in white Money (as by the foregoing Accompt appears) not onely the portage thereof was much more chargeable, but alſo the trouble of changing ſome part thereof into gold (which was then abſolutely neceſſary) took up a great ſpace of time, ſo that it could not be conveighed ſo ſpeedily as otherwiſe it might have been into the Valleys; Nor when it was there, could the whole ſumme of 65894 French Livers be ſo ſoon diſtributed as before, by reaſon that thoſe who were intruſted in the buſineſs, were but newly choſen, and therefore were to examine with all poſſible exactneſs the Accompts of thoſe who had been before intruſted in the ſame buſineſs, and alſo to rectifie all miſcarriages or inconveniences they ſhould finde to have been in the management of the Diſtribution of former Summes; And all this before they could with any Method or Order proceed to diſtribute any part of this Summe. Beſides that, this was to be as a leading Card, and a Rule for the conſtant meaſure of all future Diſtributions.

However on the 14 Jan. 1656/7 the aboveſaid Summe of 5010 l. 14. s. 9. d. or 65340 Fr. Livers, was actually diſtributed amongſt the poor people, as will appear by the following Original Acquittance, ſigned by their own hands.

body.head: A Tranſlat of the Original Acquittance of the poor People of the Valleys of Piemont, for the 65340 Fr. Livers remitted to them by Mr Morland.
body.p:
WE the Deputies of the Reformed Churches of the Valleys of Piemont, acknowledge to have received of Mr Morland, Commiſsioner Extraordinary of His most ſerene Highneſs, The Lord Protector of Great Britain, The Sum of Sixty five thouſand three hundred and forty French Livers, ariſing out of the Collections made in Great Britain for our relief. For the which Summe we acquit and diſcharge the ſaid Mr Morland, returning him our hearty thanks for the care he hath taken of us, in
the procuring and remitting the ſame to us; and above all, The Charitable Givers, for the Compaſſion they have had of our pitiful eſtate.

div.p: The true Original of this Acquittance (being ſubſcribed by ſeveral perſons, whoſe Names it is thought fit for ſeveral weighty reaſons to conceal) was delivered by M. Morland into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners, appointed by His Highneſs & the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs.
About the 20. Novemb. 56/7 Mr Morland received Orders in a Letter from Mr Secretary Thurloe for his return into England, where he arrived the 20 Decemb. 56/7.

Upon his arrival here, he gave an Accompt to His Highneſs and the Council of his management of the whole Affair, and likewiſe of the ſad condition the people were then in. And not many weeks after, having received intelligence that they ſtood in need of freſh ſupplies, he ſollicited in their behalf, and upon the 27 of Jan. 1656. an Order was granted as follows:
Copy of the Order of His Highneſs and the Council, for the remitting of 2000 l. ſterl. into the Valleys of Piemont. Tueſday 27 January 1656. At the Council at Whitehall.
VVHereas the Committee for the Protestants in the Valleys of Piemont have offered it to His Highneſs and the Council as their humble opinion, That two thouſand pounds of the Collection-money for the ſaid Proteſtants be ſpeedily remitted beyond ſea for their preſent relief; Ordered by His Highneſs the Lord Protector and the Council, That Sr Thomas Vyner and Sr Chriſtopher Pack, Knights, Treaſurers for the ſaid Collection-moneys, do, out of the ſaid Moneys remaining in their hands, forthwith pay two Thouſand pounds to Mr Morland, who is to take care for remitting the ſame in the most ſafe and convenient way, for the ſaid Proteſtants preſent relief.
Hen. Scobell Clerk of the Council.

Now Mr Morland, though he received this Order from His Highneſs and the Council, yet foraſmuch as he had no particular Inſtructions concerning the remitting any Sums for the future, before his departure from Geneva, he durſt not engage to remit the Moneys before he had firſt wrote to the party who remitted the former Sums, to know his minde, and ſo to prevent all difficulties; and ſo it was a Moneth after the receipt of his Orders, before he could give punctual directions to his Correſpondents beyond ſea, for the remiſſion of it. But ſo ſoon as ever he had received an anſwer from beyond ſea, he forthwith gave ſuch Inſtructions as were neceſſary, and on the 5th of April, 1657. the poor people actually received the Moneys, as appears by their following formal Acquittance.

body.head: A Tranſlat of the Original Acquittance of the poor people of the Valleys of Plemont, for the Value of the laſt 2000 l. ſterl.
body.p:
VVE, the Deputies of the Reformed Churches of the Valleys of Piemont, confeſs to have received of Mr Morland the Sum of Twenty ſix Thouſand one hundred and twenty ſix Livers; The which ſum was diſtributed amongſt all our Churches, that is to ſay, to every one according to their loſſes and most urgent neceſſities, conformable to the aboveſaid Mr Morland's former Inſtructions for that purpoſe; And as the ſaid ſum is a part of the Collections made in England, we return our moſt humble thanks to His
Highneſs The Lord Protector, and pray God for the proſperity of His Perſon, and of the whole Church and flouriſhing Commonwealth of Great Britain.

div.p: The true Original of this Acquittance, being ſubſcribed by ſeveral perſons, (whoſe names it is thought fit for ſeveral weighty reaſons to conceal) was delivered by Mr Morland into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſſioners, appointed by His Highneſs and the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs.

About three Moneths after the diſtribution of the 2000 l. aboveſaid, Mr Morland, having received certain Intelligence of many new grievances and vexations which thoſe poor people then lay under, by reaſon of the extraordinary hatred and malice of their popiſh Adverſaries, communicated the ſame to the Right Honorable Commiſſioners appointed by His Highneſs and the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs, who immediately repreſented the ſame to Mr Secretary Thurloe, and he to His Highneſs and the Council, and thereupon there was an Order iſſued out as follows:

body.head: Tueſday 28 July, 1657. At the Council at Whitehall.
body.p: VVHereas the Committee for the Valleys of Piemont have by their Order of the 22th of July instant, offered it to His Highneſs and the Council as their humble advice, That one thouſand pounds may be forthwith tranſmitted as formerly, for relief of the poor Protestants in the Valleys of Piemont; Ordered by His Highneſs The Lord Protector and the Council, That Sr Thomas Vyner, & Sr Chriſtopher Pack Knights, Treaſurers for the Moneys collected for Relief of the ſaid Proteſtants, do out of the Moneys remaining in their hands of the ſaid Collections, forthwith pay One thouſand pounds to Mr Morland, who is to take care for remitting the ſame, in the most ſafe and convenient way, for the ſaid Proteſtants preſent ſupport.

closer.signed: W. Jeſſop Clerk of the Council.

div.p: Mr Morland, upon the receipt of the aboveſaid Order, did his utmoſt endeavour to have remitted and ſent over the Moneys the ſame week; but it ſo falling out, that at that very time the great abundance of violent rains that fell in thoſe parts, cauſed ſuch mighty flouds that there was no paſſage, for at leaſt a moneth or ſix weeks ſpace into thoſe Valleys, the remiſſion was by that means much retarded; however upon the 24h of Octob. 1657. it was actually received by the poor people, as appears by their following Authentique Acquittance;

body.head: A Tranſlat of the Original Acquittance of the poor People of the Valleys of Piemont, for the laſt 1000 l. remitted to them by M. Morland.
body.p: WE the Deputies, &c. of the Reformed Churches in the Valleys of Piemont, confeſs to have actually and really received of Mr. Morland, the ſum of Thirteen thouſand and three Livers, and thirteen Sols Turnois, as part of the charitable Benevolence of our beloved and honored Brethren in Jeſus Chriſt, of Great Britain; And this beſides and over and above all other Sums which have been remitted formerly into our hands, the which Sum of Thirteen thouſand three Livers, and thirteen Sols Turnois, hath been diſtributed amongſt all our Churches in a juſt proportion, and with a due reſpect to the number of perſons, the greateſt ſufferers, and their preſent more urgent neceſsities; For the which we return the Donors all the Thanks we are able for their holy and exemplary Charity toward us, beſeeching from the bottom of our hearts the Father of Mercies to be their abundant Reward.

div.p: The true Original of this Acquittance, being ſubſcribed by ſeveral perſons (whoſe names it is thought fit for ſeveral weighty reaſons to conceal) was delivered by Mr Morland into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſſioners, appointed by His Highneſs and the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs.

This very Moneth was not many days expired, before Mr. Morland received Intelligence of the renewed Wants and Exigences of thoſe poor People, which he immediately communicated to the Right Honorable Mr. Secretary Thurloe, and Mr. Secretary again to His Highneſs and the Council, who forthwith cauſed a Meeting of the Commiſsioners, and upon further advice with them, granted an Order as followeth:

opener.dateline: Monday 25th November 1657. At the Council at White-Hall.

body.p: ORdered by His Highneſs the Lord Protector and the Council, That over and above the ſums of money already tranſmitted to the poor Proteſtants of Piemont, out of the Moneys collected for them, there be the ſum of Fifteen hundred pounds more forthwith ſent unto them for their relief; And that the Committee for the Affairs of the ſaid Proteſtants do take care the ſame be ſent accordingly, and that the Treaſurers be allowed 2 l. per Cent. for the charge of tranſmitting the ſame upon their Accompt.

closer.signed: W. Jeſſop Clerk of the Council.

div.p: Mr. Morland upon the receipt of this Order, by the direction of the Right Honorable Commiſſioners, remitted over the ſaid Sum of 1500 l. in the ſame maner and method as he had remitted the former Sums, and accordingly hath received certain advice of the ſafe arrival thereof in thoſe parts; but by reaſon of the incredible quantities of ſnow which have lyen ever ſince upon thoſe Mountains, which have ſtopt up all paſſages of late, the poor peoples Original Acquittance is not yet come to his hands, for the actual Diſtribution thereof; moreover he daily expects the ſame, and having received it, ſhall deliver it into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſſioners.

It will be neceſſary in the cloſe of this Accompt, to advertiſe the Readers, that beſides what was remitted over from England into the Valleys, there were ſeveral ſmaller Sums given out to ſome particular perſons here in England, under the notion of eminent Sufferers for and in that Cauſe, and that upon pretended Recommendations from the poor people themſelves and their Deputies, which they then preſented to the Right Honorable Commiſſioners during Mr. Morlands abode at Geneva; but two of them, by name Captain Raymond and Chriſtiana Ʋlrick, having moſt wickedly and treacherouſly counterfeited thoſe their ſaid Atteſtations and other papers (as it afterwards plainly appeared when it was too late upon Mr. Morlands return into England, who by the Order of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners made a further ſearch into that buſineſs) it is thought fit that thoſe their unworthy actions be made manifeſt to all men. The firſt of them immediately upon Mr. Morlands return, having a guilty conſcience, fled beyond ſea; and the laſt upon Examination, confeſſed to one of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners, that ſhe had moſt wretchedly ſuffered her ſelf to be tempted, and prevailed upon by the devil, to the commiſsion of that ſo hainous and foul a ſin.

This is now the ſum and ſubſtance of the Accompt which Mr. Morland hath in part formerly, and the reſt of late delivered into the hands of the Right Honorable Commiſsioners, appointed by His Highneſs and the Council for the Management of thoſe Affairs; But for the eaſe and better ſatisfaction of all thoſe that deſire more fully to inform themſelves herein, and that they may as it were with one glance of their eye, have a full proſpect of all the Receipts and Disburſements of or upon the ſaid Collected Moneys, as well at home as abroad, they are deſired to peruſe the following General Accompt.

div.p: As for the Moneys that yet remain in the hands of the Treaſurers, the good People of this Nation are deſired to believe and be aſſured, that it hath hitherto been His Highneſs exceeding great Care that no part of the Collected Moneys might be diſtributed or delivered out, but by the advice, and through the hands of perſons of known Honor and approved Fidelity; ſo likewiſe it ſhall be His conſtant endeavor, that what yet remains, or ſhall hereafter be collected and laid up in the hands of the Treaſurers (who are as ready now as ever, to receive what ſhall be further collected) ſhall be improved for the beſt advantage of thoſe for whom it was (or ſhall be) ſolely intended. For which end and purpoſe His Highneſs, after mature Conſultation had both with His Commiſsioners at home, and His publique Miniſters abroad, hath already cauſed ſome part thereof to be put out to Intereſt in ſure hands (but ſo, that it may be called in upon urgent occaſion) and for the future will take ſuch Reſolutions as the Neceſsities of thoſe poor People, and the Circumſtances of their Condition ſhall require, which (the Lord knows) is now as ſad as ever in many reſpects, and without the ſame miraculous hand of Providence that hath hitherto preſerved them, muſt in a ſhort time inevitably periſh. Wherefore if there be any charitable Souls who have yet contributed nothing to the relief of their poor diſtreſſed Brethren, let them pleaſe to peruſe the following Diſcourſe, and it may be they may finde there ſuch Arguments as may awaken them, and quicken their hearts to the performance of ſo good and Chriſtian a Work.

div.head: A Brief Accompt of the preſent State and Condition of the poor Proteſtants in the Valleys of Piemont: Together with A Serious Exhortation to all thoſe who have hitherto contributed nothing towards the Relief of their diſtreſſed Brethren, that if the Lord ſo pleaſe, their hearts may be yet moved to the performance of ſo good and charitable a work.

q.p: 11 If thou forbear to deliver them that are drawn unto death, and thoſe that are ready to be ſlain,

12 If thou ſaist, Behold we knew it not; doth not he that pondereth the heart, conſider it? and he that keepeth thy ſoul, doth not he know it? and ſhall not he render to every man according to his work?

div.p: IF Words in ſeaſon be (or at • aſt ought to be) acceptable things, then I truſt I may, without offence, here in the cloſe of this Narrative, entreat all thoſe who have hitherto contributed nothing towards the relief and ſupport of their poor diſtreſſed Brethren, to ſuffer a word of ſerious Exhortation, as hoping (if the Lord ſo pleaſe) it may have ſuch bleſſed effects upon their ſpirits, that they may at laſt both cheerfully partake in the work, and hereafter have a ſutable ſhare in the reward.

The plain truth is, it may be righteouſly preſumed from what hath been already ſaid, that all ſober and ingenuous perſons will be ſo far from reſerving in their mindes the leaſt ſcruple as touching the honeſt and faithful Adminiſtration of the collected Moneys, that on the contrary all thoſe who have contributed freely, will have much ſatisfaction in what they have already done, and be the more ready to do the like for the future, as there ſhall be occaſion; and thoſe who have either come off coldly, or given nothing at all, will account it as a ſingular mercy of God towards them to have ſuch an opportunity as this is, afforded them, of redeeming the time, and of making recompence for their former backwardneſs, by drawing out now at laſt a larger portion of their love, and by doubling the effects of their charity and tender compaſſions towards the relieving of their diſtreſſed fellow members.

And indeed, have they but a heart to the work, I ſhall ſoon lead them where they ſhall even ſmite upon their breſts, and their hearts ſhall even melt within them, to hear the lamentable and woful cries of above ten Thouſand ſouls, who are at this very day ſitting among the potſherds, with ſackcloth and aſhes ſpread under them, and lifting up their voice with weeping, in the words of Job, when he was now in the depth of his miſery and anguiſh, Have pitie on us, have pitie on us, O ye our friends, for the hand of God hath touched us!

If there be any who are curious to know who theſe men are, and what was their Fathers houſe, I ſhall endeavor to ſatisfie them in a few words at preſent, referring them for a larger Diſcourſe upon that ſubject, to the History of the Evangelical Churches of the Valleys of Piemont, which will, God willing, ſpeedily preſent it ſelf to publique view.

Theſe poor creatures are the children and off-ſpring of thoſe ancient Inhabitants of the Valleys of Piemont, who have born teſtimony to the truth in the purity thereof, ever ſince the days of Christ and his Apostles; And though they have been ofttimes
furiouſly aſſaulted by the ſons of violence, yet God hath always by a miraculous providence preſerved thoſe little ſparks in the greateſt flouds of perſecutions, that either the ſubtilty or malice of their enemies could ever raiſe againſt them, according to that excellent Character the learned Beza gives of them in his Treatiſe of the famous Pillars of Learning and Religion.Icones Theod Be • æ de Valdenſ. Valdenſes liceat mihi Veteris Chriſtianæ purioris Eccleſiæ ſemen vocare, ut pote quos constet verè admirabili Dei Providentia; neque illis infinitis tempestatibus, quibus est per tot ſecula Chriſtianus Orbis concuſſus, & occidens tandem à Pſeud-epiſcopo Romano miſerè oppreſſus, neque adverſus illos propriè excitatis horribilibus perſecutionibus eò adduci potuiſſent, ut Idolomaniæ, & Romanæ tyrannidi aſſentirentur, i. e. As for the Waldenſes, give me leave to ſtyle them the very ſeed of the Primitive and purer Christian Church, as thoſe who have been manifeſtly upheld by the admirable Providence of God; ſo that neither thoſe infinite ſtorms and tempests, whereby the whole Chriſtian world hath been ſhaken for ſo many Ages together, and at length the Western parts ſo miſerably opprest by the Biſhop of Rome, falſly ſo called; nor thoſe horrible perſecutions, which have been directly raiſed against them, were ever able ſo far to prevail upon them, as to make them yeeld a voluntary ſubjection to the Romiſh Tyranny and Idolatry.

Yea there are divers ſober and learned men in the neighboring and adjacent parts, who confidently aſſert from ſome late diſcoveries, That this was the very deſert whither the woman fled when ſhe was perſecuted by the Dragon with ſeven heads and ten horns. Revel. 12.6. Cant. 2.14. And that it was in the Clefts of theſe very Rocks, and in the ſecret places of the ſtairs of theſe very Valleys, that the Dove of Christ remained in thoſe dark and gloomy ſeaſons of the 8, 9 and 10 Centuries, at which time alſo the Italian foxes began to ſpoil the Vines with the tender grapes, Cant. 2.15.

Theſe things I have the rather hinted, (though briefly) to ſignifie how precious theſe people have always been in the eyes of the great God of heaven and earth, and conſequently to heighten our love and eſteem of the ſcattered remnant of their ſeed, of whom a conſiderable number have been moſt cruelly murdered and maſſacred, within theſe few late years, and whoſe ſouls are now under the Altar, waiting and expecting till God avenge their bloud upon them that dwell upon the earth: Some of their Virgins raviſh't, and afterwards abuſed in ſo horrid a maner as is not fit to be mentioned, till ſuch time as they gave up the ghoſt in unſpeakable pain and anguiſh! The brains of innocent and tender infants ſodden and eaten by their murderers! The fleſh of ſome pluckt off their bones (while they were yet alive) till they were become meer Skeletons or Anatomies! Many feeble, ſick and aged perſons of 90, and 100 years moſt inhumanely burnt in their beds! others moſt barbarouſly treated without any reſpect to their hoary heads or gray hairs! with a multitude of other ſtrange, and almoſt unheard of cruelties, which would be too long here to rehearſe.

Now as for thoſe of them that ſurvived and eſcaped the rage of thoſe men of bloud (which are the people I now recommend to your Chriſtian charitie and pitie) alas! they were then immediately expoſed to the extremities of hunger, cold and nakedneſs, and almoſt all the miſeries of this life; being forced to wander up and down upon the craggy Rocks and ſnowy Mountains, in a moſt deſolate and forlorn condition; yea and even to this preſent hour they hunger, and thirst, and are naked, and buffeted, and have no certain dwelling place, 1 Cor. 4.11. To this very day, they labor under moſt heavy burthens which are laid upon their ſhoulders by thoſe rigid Taskmasters of the Church of Rome. To this very day the enemies of the Truth plough and make long furrows upon the backs of thoſe poor creatures, By forbidding them all maner of traffique or commerce for their ſuſtenance; By robbing them of their goods and Eſtates; By driving them in a moſt ſavage maner from their ancient houſes and habitations, and forcing them to ſell their birth-right for a meſs of pottage; By baniſhing their Miniſters, who are the ſhepherds of the flocks, that ſo the wolves may the better come in, and devour the ſheep; By raviſhing their young women and maidens; yea by murthering many innocent ſouls, as they paſs along the high-ways about their private occaſions; By cruel mockings and revilings; By continual menacings and
threats of another Maſſacre, if poſſible, ſeven-fold more bloudy then the former: What ſhall I ſay? Thoſe very Valleys, where they inhabit at this day, are 〈◊〉 the indefatigable induſtry of their Popiſh adverſaries made no other then a priſon o •
••• geon, to which the Fort of La Torre ſerves as a door, where they may let in (when they pleaſe) a troop of murderers, utterly to deſtroy and exterminate thoſe poor ſilly wretches. To all this I muſt adde, (which indeed is moſt of all conſiderable as to the drawing forth your hearts to contribute towards their preſent relief) that notwithſtanding all thoſe large ſupplies, which have been hitherto ſent them, either from England or Forein States, yet ſo great is the number of thoſe hungry creatures, and ſo grievous are the oppreſſions of their Popiſh enemies, who lay in wait to bereave them of whatſoever is given them, and ſnatch at every morſel of meat that goes into their mouths, that verily, ſome of them are at this very day ready ever and anon to eat their own fleſh for want of bread. The tongue of the ſuckling is ready to cleave to the roof of his mouth, and the young children ask bread, and no man gives it unto them: And in many places the young and the old lye on the ground in the ſtreets.
In ſum, Curæ l • ves loquuntur, ingentes ſtupent. Senec. Trag. in Hippolyt.

Their miſeries are more ſad and grievous then words can expreſs; and they are in a maner dying while they yet live: No grapes in their vineyards: No cattle in their fields: No herds in their ſtals: No corn in their gardners: No meal in their barrel: No oil in their cruſe: The ſtock which was gathered for them by the good people of this Nation, waſting apace, and when that is once ſpent, they muſt inevitably periſh, except you are now pleaſed to lend your helping hand as other good Chriſtians before you have done, and ſo make ſuch an addition to that Sum which yet remains, that the Intereſt thereof may in ſome maner give them a being and ſubſiſtence in the world, and ſo the Capital remain entire, to be ready upon any occaſion (which God of his mercy prevent) in caſe thoſe poor creatures ſhould meet with freſh aſſaults from their Popiſh enemies. And all till ſuch time as Providence ſhall finde out ſome way for their ſettlement and re-eſtabliſhment.

True it is, I cannot but expect that ſome covetous, or ill-affected to the cauſe of Chriſt and his people, ſhould here ſtep in, and throw on the cold water of ſelf-intereſt, and carnal objections, to quench if poſſible the fire of your Chriſtian zeal. I ſay, ſome will certainly here object, and ſay, But if there be ſo many thouſands remaining, which are yet undistributed, what need is there (at least for the preſent) of any further ſupplies?
I anſwer,

1. Though there are ſeveral Thouſands of pounds remaining, yet there are alſo ſeveral Thouſands of thoſe poor creatures to be daily fed, clothed and ſhelter'd with it; and ten thouſand times ten thouſand things they ſtill ſtand in need of.

2. God alone knows how far off may yet be the time of their re-eſtabliſhment in their ancient habitations and priviledges: And if ſo, ſo ſoon as ever the ſtock they have at preſent is once ſpent, their caſe will be ſeven-fold more lamentable and deſperate then before.

3. This is now the ſecond opportunity the Lord hath in mercy given you of relieving his poor Saints; and let me tell you, whoever ye are that ſhut up your bowels now, it may be a third opportunity may never be afforded you. Thoſe poor wretches may poſſibly be taken out of the miſeries of this life, and you in judgement have the ſame afflictions or worſe befall you; yea, the time may come, when your own Conſciences may ſadly reflect upon you as guilty, in ſome ſenſe, of the bloud of theſe poor men, and of a tacit compliance with their murderers, there being no ſo great difference between the hard-heartedneſs of him that finding his neighbor in the ditch, offers not to help him out, and the cruelty of the man that firſt threw him in. Wherefore if you now forbear to deliver them that are drawn unto death, and thoſe that are ready to be ſlain; If you ſay, Behold we know it not; doth not he that pondereth the heart, conſider it? and he that keepeth your ſouls, doth not he know it? and ſhall not he render to every man according to his works?

If therefore ſo many thouſand diſtreſſed ſouls be any objects of your Chriſtian Charity if the good example of your compaſſionate Brethren may be any meaſure of yo •
• ctions; if the common Law of Nature be at all obligatory; yea, if the Commands, Promiſes and Threats of GOD himſelf throughout the Holy Scriptures be of any force with you, then think and meditate on theſe things.

It is very remarkable, That when Our Savior would make a lively deſcription and repreſentation of the great Day of Judgement, he ſeems to take no other meaſure for the final ſentence of Condemnation or Abſolution, then the pure performance of omiſſion of actions of Charity towards his poor diſtreſſed Members. As for example, I was hungry, and ye gave me meat, or ye gave me none: I was thirsty, and ye gave me drink, or ye gave me none: I was naked, and ye clothed me, or ye clothed me not: ſick and in priſon, and ye viſited me, or ye viſited me not. Matth. 25.34, 35, 36, 42, 43.

Wherefore I ſay, if on the one ſide you would not ſwallow down riches to vomit them up again; if you would not have the increaſe of your houſes to depart; nor in the fulneſs of your ſufficiency be in want; if you would not have your riches to corrupt, and your garments to be moth-eaten; if you would not have your gold to canker, and the rust thereof to witneſs against you at the last day: And on the other ſide, if you your ſelves would willingly finde pitie and relief in the day of your calamity; if you would be preſerved in ſix troubles, and in ſeven have no evil touch you; if you would have the loins of the poor and needy to bear witneſs for you another day; and the bleſſing of him that was ready to periſh to come upon you; if you would be bleſſed in your Houſes, and in your Children; in your cattel, and in your fields, in your barns, and in your ſtore: In a word, if you would aſſure your ſelves either of the comforts of this, or the treaſures of a better life, then turn the deaf ear to all the ſuggeſtions of Satan, the world, or your own carnal and covetous Principles: Then cast your bread upon the waters, and you ſhall finde it after many days: Then give a portion to ſeven, and alſo to eight, not knowing what evil may come upon the earth: Then give, and it ſhall be given to you again, in full meaſure, heaped up and running over, for every Omer an Ephah; and for every grain, a talent. Be aſſured, that not the value of a cup of cold water that you give to theſe poor creatures in the name of Diſciples, ſhall ever loſe its reward. No, no, whoever thou art, if thou draw out thy ſoul to the hungry, and ſatisfie the afflicted ſoul, then ſhall thy light riſe in obſcurity, and thy darkneſs ſhall be as the noon day: If thou cover the naked, and hide not thy ſelf from thy own fleſh; Then ſhall the Lord guide thee continually, and ſatisfie thy ſoul in drought, and make fat thy bones; Then ſhall thy righteouſneſs go before thee, and the glory of the Lord ſhall be thy rereward. I ſay reſt aſſuredly confident, that the God and Father of mercies ſhall recompenſe this your loving kindeneſs, and repay you a thouſand fold into your boſoms, either in this life, or that which is to come.
div.closer: This is the Faith, and this is the hearty Prayer of Your moſt humble and affectionate ſervant in CHRIST JESUS, Samuel Morland.
